Matrix Algebra

Rafael A. Irizarry
October 9, 2014

Motivation

  • Our data is usually saved in matrices.

  • In the gene expression example data, XX, was 8793×2088793×208

  • Say you want to compute the average of each column

Matrix Notation

  • Let XX be a data matrix with NN rows and pp columns

  • The vector of column averages:

(1N∑i=1NXi,1,…,1N∑i=1NXi,p)(1N∑i=1NXi,1,…,1N∑i=1NXi,p)

can be written like this AXAX with A=(1N,…,1N)A=(1N,…,1N)

Matrix Notation

Here are the matrix operations

AX=(1N1N…1N)⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟AX=(1N1N…1N)(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p)

=(X¯1X¯2…X¯N)=(X¯1X¯2…X¯N)

Matrix Notation

Here are the row averages:

XB=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜1/p1/p⋮1/p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X¯1X¯2⋮X¯q⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟XB=(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p)(1/p1/p⋮1/p)=(X¯1X¯2⋮X¯q)

Matrix Notation (more general)

AX=(a1a2…aN)⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟AX=(a1a2…aN)(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p)

=(∑Ni=1aiXi,1…∑Ni=1aiXi,p)=(∑i=1NaiXi,1…∑i=1NaiXi,p)
Convenient and fast for coding

Matrix Notation

  • Say for each gene you want to compute
    1. the average across all samples
    2. the difference between males and females

Matrix Notation

⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜1/p1/p⋮1/pa1a2ap⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p)(1/pa11/pa2⋮1/pap)
with
aj={−1/NF1/NMif female if maleaj={−1/NFif female 1/NMif male

with NFNF=number of females and NMNM=number of males.

Matrix Notation (even more general)

AX=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜a1,1a2,1aM,1a1,2a2,2aM,2……⋮…a1,Na2,NaM,N⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟AX=(a1,1a1,2…a1,Na2,1a2,2…a2,N⋮aM,1aM,2…aM,N)(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p)

=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜∑Ni=1a1,iXi,1∑Ni=1aM,iXi,1…⋮…∑Ni=1a1,iXi,p∑Ni=1aM,iXi,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟=(∑i=1Na1,iXi,1…∑i=1Na1,iXi,p⋮∑i=1NaM,iXi,1…∑i=1NaM,iXi,p)

Regression Models

We used regression with our Baseball data. For example

Yi=β0+Xiβ1+εi,i=1,…,NYi=β0+Xiβ1+εi,i=1,…,N

with YiYi = runs for team ii and XiXi = BB for team ii.

We need to find the β0,β1β0,β1 pair that minimizes

∑i=1N(Yi−β0−Xiβ1)2∑i=1N(Yi−β0−Xiβ1)2

How do we do this?

Linear Algebra Representation

We can write it like this:

⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜Y1Y2⋮YN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜11⋮1⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟β0+⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1X2⋮XN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟β1+⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜ε1ε2⋮εN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟(Y1Y2⋮YN)=(11⋮1)β0+(X1X2⋮XN)β1+(ε1ε2⋮εN)

The YY column is a point in ℝNRN

The 11 and XX vectors define a subspace, each point defined by the pair (β0,β1)∈ℝ2(β0,β1)∈R2.

Projections

Recall: The projection of the point YY to the smaller space minimizes the distance.

Simplest example

y⃗ ∈ℝNy→∈RN and L⊂ℝNL⊂RN is the space spanned by

v⃗ =⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜1⋮1⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟;L={cv⃗ ;c∈ℝ}v→=(1⋮1);L={cv→;c∈R}

What cc minimizes distance between cv⃗ cv→ and y⃗ y→?

Answer: The projection of y⃗ y→ onto LL:

ProjL(y⃗ )=ĉ v⃗ ProjL(y→)=c^v→

So how do we find ĉ c^?

Simplest example

The projection is orthogonal to the space so:

(y⃗ −ĉ v⃗ )⋅v⃗ =0(y→−c^v→)⋅v→=0

y⃗ ⋅v⃗ −ĉ v⃗ ⋅v⃗ =0y→⋅v→−c^v→⋅v→=0

ĉ =y⃗ ⋅v⃗ v⃗ ⋅v⃗ c^=y→⋅v→v→⋅v→

Simplest example

ĉ =y⃗ ⋅v⃗ v⃗ ⋅v⃗ c^=y→⋅v→v→⋅v→

Going back to our original notation this means β̂ 0=Y¯β^0=Y¯

In this case calculus would have been just as easy:

∂∂β0∑i=1N(Yi−β0)2=0⟹−2∑i=1N(Yi−β0)=0⟹∂∂β0∑i=1N(Yi−β0)2=0⟹−2∑i=1N(Yi−β0)=0⟹

Nβ0=∑i=1NYi⟹β0^=Y¯Nβ0=∑i=1NYi⟹β0^=Y¯

Regression Model

Make it slightly more complicated.

The space is now

L={β0v⃗ 0+β1v⃗ 1;β⃗ =(β0,β1)∈ℝ2}L={β0v→0+β1v→1;β→=(β0,β1)∈R2}

with

v⃗ 0=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜11⋮1⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟ and v⃗ 1=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1X2⋮XN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟v→0=(11⋮1) and v→1=(X1X2⋮XN)

The Transpose

The columns become the rows

X=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1XN,1……⋮…X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟,X⊤=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X1,2X1,p……⋮…XN,1XN,2XN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟X=(X1,1…X1,pX2,1…X2,p⋮XN,1…XN,p),X⊤=(X1,1…XN,1X1,2…XN,2⋮X1,p…XN,p)

Variance

This helps us define projections but also:

If XX is N×pN×p matrix of features for which the columns have average 0,

S=1NX⊤XS=1NX⊤X

  • is called the sample covariance matrix
  • Si,iSi,i is the variance of column ii
  • Si,jSi,j entry is the covariance between columns ii and jj.
  • Si,jSi,iSj,j‾‾‾‾‾√Si,jSi,iSj,j
    is the correlation

Regression Model

Let X=[v⃗ 0v⃗ 1]X=[v→0v→1]. It's a N×2N×2 matrix

Any point LL can be writen as XβXβ.

The orthogonal projection must have

X⊤(y⃗ −Xβ⃗ )=0X⊤(y→−Xβ→)=0

X⊤Xβ⃗ =X⊤yX⊤Xβ→=X⊤y

β⃗ =(X⊤X)−1X⊤yβ→=(X⊤X)−1X⊤y

Regression Models

In general, we can write this

Yi=β0+Xi,1β1+…Xi,pβp+εi,i=1,…,NYi=β0+Xi,1β1+…Xi,pβp+εi,i=1,…,N
as

⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜Y1Y2⋮YN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜11⋮1⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟β0+⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,1X2,1⋮XN,1⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟β1+⋯+⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜X1,pX2,p⋮XN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟βp+⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜ε1ε2⋮εN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟(Y1Y2⋮YN)=(11⋮1)β0+(X1,1X2,1⋮XN,1)β1+⋯+(X1,pX2,p⋮XN,p)βp+(ε1ε2⋮εN)

Regression Models

We can simplify to:

Y=Xβ+εY=Xβ+ε

with

Y=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜Y1⋮YN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟,X=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜⎜111X1,1X2,1⋮XN,1………X1,pX2,pXN,p⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟⎟,β=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜β1⋮βp⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟,ε=⎛⎝⎜⎜⎜ε1⋮εN⎞⎠⎟⎟⎟Y=(Y1⋮YN),X=(1X1,1…X1,p1X2,1…X2,p⋮1XN,1…XN,p),β=(β1⋮βp),ε=(ε1⋮εN)

Regression Model

Solution is still

β̂ =(X⊤X)−1X⊤Yβ^=(X⊤X)−1X⊤Y

Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)

We have a data matrix with NN observations (rows) and pp columns.

We can write our data matrix as

X=UDV⊤, with X=UDV⊤, with 

  • UU is N×pN×p with U⊤U=IU⊤U=I
  • VV is p×pp×p with V⊤V=IV⊤V=I and
  • DD is p×pp×p diagonal matrix

We are changing basis: XV=UDXV=UD

And can change back XVV⊤=XXVV⊤=X

SVD

  • Say the columns of XX are perfectly correlated

  • Then we really have just one column, the SVD catches this:

X = U[:,0] d[0,0] Vh[0,:]

Motivating SVD

Consider this simple linear combination:

Δj=(Y1,j,…,YN,j)′(1/N1,…,1/N1,−1/N2,…,−1/N2)=Δj=(Y1,j,…,YN,j)′(1/N1,…,1/N1,−1/N2,…,−1/N2)=

1N1∑i=1N1Yi,j−1N2∑i=N1+1NYi,j,N2=N−N11N1∑i=1N1Yi,j−1N2∑i=N1+1NYi,j,N2=N−N1

Try to find the N1N1 that maximizes the variance

1p∑j=1pΔ2j1p∑j=1pΔj2
